{"author":{"id":"e5b2723c1054aec2ffeb31b2a49d5d51632ae8ee05f97e67a92344953cea52a1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1519322275,"nonce":"HidQ74qRmIA3ha1nChC+iEGq04E=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUyOTk0NTA0MTI=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1738","origin":"github"},"title":"Possible to add more options to melt/cast?","message":"Adding more flexibility to [reshape2's melt/cast](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/tree/master/tools/reshape2/) would help with more complicated situations (multiple id vars). For example, say I have a table with peptide, sample, and intensity in each that sample (see bottom for table creation):\n\n```\n\u003edf\n     pep sample       int\n1   pep1  samp1 1013.1541\n2   pep2  samp1  910.2090\n3   pep3  samp1 1135.1945\n4   pep4  samp1 1042.0075\n5   pep5  samp2  971.1540\n6   pep6  samp2 1136.4561\n7   pep7  samp2 1193.8725\n8   pep8  samp3  763.9017\n9   pep9  samp3  940.5886\n10 pep10  samp3  945.5447\n```\nI want to get it into wide format, where each column is a sample:\n```\n     pep    samp1    samp2    samp3\n1   pep1 1013.154       NA       NA\n2  pep10       NA       NA 945.5447\n3   pep2  910.209       NA       NA\n4   pep3 1135.194       NA       NA\n5   pep4 1042.007       NA       NA\n6   pep5       NA  971.154       NA\n7   pep6       NA 1136.456       NA\n8   pep7       NA 1193.873       NA\n9   pep8       NA       NA 763.9017\n10  pep9       NA       NA 940.5886\n```\n\nThis is how I'm doing it with `reshape2`: \n\n```\ndcast(df, formula = pep ~ sample, value.var = \"int\")\n```\n\nAs you can see, I don't need `melt`, but I do need the capability to specify  `value.var` and the formula. Would it be possible to add more parameters to the `melt` and `cast` tools to accomplish this? Being able to specify the columns on the left and right hand sides of the formula and the value var column would help. Currently, the tool can only return the original data frame:\n\n```\n\u003e dcast(melt(df), formula = ... ~ variable)\nUsing pep, sample as id variables\n     pep sample       int\n1   pep1  samp1 1013.1541\n2  pep10  samp3  945.5447\n3   pep2  samp1  910.2090\n4   pep3  samp1 1135.1945\n5   pep4  samp1 1042.0075\n6   pep5  samp2  971.1540\n7   pep6  samp2 1136.4561\n8   pep7  samp2 1193.8725\n9   pep8  samp3  763.9017\n10  pep9  samp3  940.5886\n```\n\nAll code: \n```\nlibrary(reshape2)\nnrows \u003c- 10\npep \u003c- paste(\"pep\", 1:nrows, sep=\"\")\nprot \u003c- paste(\"prot\", 1:nrows, sep=\"\")\nset.seed(1010)\nint \u003c- rnorm(10, mean = 1000, sd = 100)\nsample \u003c- c(rep(\"samp1\", 4), rep(\"samp2\", 3), rep(\"samp3\", 3))\n\ndf \u003c- data.frame(pep, int)\ndcast(df, formula = pep ~ sample, value.var = \"int\")\n```","files":null}]}